ls: Lists the contents of a directory.
cd: Changes the current working directory.
mkdir: Creates a new directory.
touch: Creates an empty file or updates the access and modification times of an existing file.
rm: Removes a file or directory.
cp: Copies a file or directory.
mv: Moves or renames a file or directory.
cat: Displays the contents of a file.
grep: Searches for a pattern in a file.
chmod: Changes the permissions of a file or directory.
chown: Changes the ownership of a file or directory.
sudo: Runs a command with administrative privileges.
top: Displays real-time information about running processes.
ps: Lists the currently running processes.
kill: Terminates a running process.
These commands only scratch the surface of what you can do in Linux, but they should get you started!




Raj Kumar
linux commands
Here are some additional Linux commands you may find useful:

man: Displays the manual page for a command.
pwd: Prints the current working directory.
echo: Prints text to the console.
date: Displays the current date and time.
hostname: Displays the name of the current host.
ifconfig: Displays network interface configuration.
ping: Tests network connectivity to a remote host.
traceroute: Traces the route packets take to reach a remote host.
wget: Downloads files from the internet.
tar: Creates or extracts tar archives.
zip/unzip: Creates or extracts zip archives.
ssh: Connects to a remote host over SSH.
scp: Copies files to or from a remote host over SSH.
history: Displays a list of previously executed commands.
find: Searches for files in a directory hierarchy based on various criteria.
There are many more Linux commands available, but these should give you a good starting point. Remember, you can use the man command to get help on any of these commands (e.g., man ls will display the manual page for the ls command).




Raj Kumar
linux commands pdf
There are many resources available online for learning Linux commands, including PDFs. Here are a few options:

"The Linux Command Line" by William Shotts: This book is available for free online and covers a wide range of Linux commands in detail. It includes examples and exercises to help you practice.

"Linux Command Line Cheat Sheet" by DaveChild: This is a one-page PDF cheat sheet that lists many common Linux commands, along with a brief description of each.

"Linux Commands Reference Cheat Sheet" by Red Hat: This is another one-page cheat sheet that lists many common Linux commands, organized by category.

"Linux Commands Cheat Sheet" by FOSS Post: This is a two-page PDF cheat sheet that includes many common Linux commands, along with examples and explanations.

"Linux Command Line Quick Reference" by Cheatography: This is a two-page PDF cheat sheet that includes many common Linux commands, organized by category.

These resources should give you a good starting point for learning Linux commands.




Raj Kumar
linux sheat sheet
Here is a basic Linux command line cheat sheet with some commonly used commands:

File management
ls: list files and directories
cd: change directory
mkdir: create a new directory
touch: create a new file
cp: copy a file or directory
mv: move a file or directory
rm: remove a file or directory
cat: display the contents of a file
Text editing
nano: open and edit a text file
vi or vim: another text editor
sed: stream editor for filtering and transforming text
awk: pattern scanning and processing language
Process management
top: display real-time information about running processes
ps: list the currently running processes
kill: terminate a running process
System information
df: display disk usage information
free: display memory usage information
uname: display system information
uptime: display how long the system has been running
Network management
ifconfig: configure network interface parameters
ping: test network connectivity to a remote host
traceroute: trace the route packets take to reach a remote host
ssh: connect to a remote host over SSH
scp: copy files to or from a remote host over SSH
This is just a basic Linux command line cheat sheet, and there are many more commands available. However, these commands should be enough to get you started with using the Linux command line.






